##Working in the south China Seafood Market, Jingzhou's first healer dictated: I was lucky

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

As of 10:03 on January 30, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in China had exceeded 7,000, reaching 7,736, with 12,167 suspected cases, 170 deaths and 124 cured and discharged cases.

Five million people reportedly left the city before it was closed. Located in the southwest of the city, Jingzhou, once the second largest city in Hubei, is one of the most populous cities in the province, after Huanggang and Xiaogan. As of 2400 hours on January 29, there were 151 confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia, three deaths and one cure in this city of 6.41 million people. The Xiaotangshan Hospital in Jingzhou has been put into operation.

In the face of a severe epidemic, hope is precious. People spoke with Wang Ping, the first and only patient to be cured in Jingzhou, and his doctor, Liu Changhua, director of the infection department of the Chest Hospital of Jingzhou city. Wang Ping, 46, had been in extreme danger after contracting the virus after working at the South China Seafood Market in Wuhan for four years. From his account, we can see that he did not suffer from the difficulties of diagnosis, the overloading of Hubei's medical system, and was properly diagnosed and treated at no cost before most people were awakened to the pandemic, he was lucky.

By Zhang Yue

Editor | locust tree

The first discharged patient from Jingzhou, Wang Ping's dictation

I felt the symptoms on the day (January 1) that the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan closed, and I felt a bit sore all over. I was at work that morning, when the seafood market was closed, I went with my boss to sell fish at the four seasons market, another seafood market in Hankou. In the afternoon, I felt sick and went to a small clinic to get an injection, go back to work the next day.

After two days feel chest tightness, began to have a fever, fever to 38 degrees 5, or to the clinic injection fever, injection temperature down a little, down to more than 37 degrees, but after half a day will be burning up.

On January 4, I saw on the news that many people in the south China seafood market had been sent to COVID-19 hospital with pneumonia. I was a little worried about myself, so I went to Wuhan Red Cross Hospital (Eleven hospital) for a check-up, drew Blood, took a picture of his lungs, and when the doctor finished, he said I had no sign of the new virus. They also did not ask me in the south China Seafood Market Work Experience, at that time everyone does not attach importance to this matter, which knew will be so serious? Wuhan just closed the seafood market.

The hospital said I was fine, I left, went to the market in the morning normal work, the afternoon to continue in the small clinic infusion. I lost two days and still didn't recover. On January 6th, I switched to another clinic. The doctor gave me two shots, but I had a fever of 102, and I said, "that's not gonNA work. ". He asked me about my symptoms. I said my chest was constricted and I had a high fever. He said I was similar to those who had pneumonia in the hospital. I said I had a check-up and showed him the film. He also said, from the film, I didn't have that symptom, but he thought I might be another virus, and suggested I go back to my hometown, Jingzhou, and get reimbursed.

At 2:30 pm on January 7, I went to Jingzhou Chest Hospital and told them directly that I came from the south China Seafood Market. The doctor with the mask was surprised and immediately went to get dressed. After ten minutes, he put me in isolation and locked me in a room.

Because I was Jingzhou's first case, the whole hospital was surprised and very concerned. Later, the nurse told me that on the evening of the 7th, the City Health Commission organized experts to study my disease. They did the tests, the C.T. , the blood work, whatever they had to do, whatever they could. At one o'clock that night, the doctor said, he thought I had COVID-19 pneumonia.

The nurse advised me not to be nervous, just to relax. Actually, I'm not nervous. I already have the disease. Why should I be nervous? I am a farmer of work, Cure Cure Cure Cure Cure, did not cure, I am not what personage again, cure dead also cure dead, how can do?

I later thought it might be because I didn't wear a mask when I worked at the South China Seafood Market. I worked there for four years, first selling vegetables, then helping others carry seafood, mainly salmon and sea bass, starting work at 3:00 a.m. every day, moving the trucks to the stalls at the market gate, sorting the fish, by the end of 10:00 a.m. , about $5,000 a month.

The sanitary condition of our market is not very good. Once you go in, the smell inside is quite big, a kind of indescribable smell. I haven't worn a mask in all the time I've been working in there. How can I wear one when I'm working?

There are more than 20 venison sellers in the market, concentrated in a passageway, snakes are piled in the doorway to sell, there are also killed chickens and ducks placed in the doorway to sell, the ground is full of oil, a walk up, we basically do not take that path, afraid of slipping.

At the time, I thought I was out of luck, that everyone I worked with was fine, no symptoms. One of my relatives was in the market for a week. He's fine. I'm the only one who's not.

In Jingzhou City Chest Hospital, I entered the isolation ward after did not come out, stayed for 21 days. I don't know what kind of medicine I used. After I finished the examination in the morning, I started to hang water (infusion) . I hung more than ten bottles every day, from morning to two o'clock in the evening.

As soon as I started getting sicker and Sicker, I started breathing hard and had a fever of 39. The virus made people too hard, the first five or six days simply can not get out of bed, people are absent-minded, no energy, even take a cell phone are boring, also can not eat food, stool and urine are in bed. Three nurses in the ward took turns taking care of me, and I was grateful to them. In our vernacular, I was a time bomb, except the doctors and nurses, who else to contact me, contact me will be infected.

Fortunately, I didn't have any other diseases, only I was infected with this virus. After more than 10 days of treatment in the ICU, I was basically stable and no longer had a fever. I was transferred to the ICU for more basic treatment, he's stabilized. I'll be out on the 27th.

Now I feel very good body, is a little thin, in hospital when I 150 pounds, now 140 pounds over.

I feel like I'm still lucky. If I were in Wuhan, I don't think I would have been able to get treatment. By the standards of the time, I was only mildly ill and probably would have been allowed to go home. But I was the only one in Jingzhou at the time, fully treated. I'm grateful they saved my life.

Oral presentation by Liu Changhua, director of the Department of Infectious Diseases

At 2:30 on the afternoon of January 7 th, Wang Ping arrived at my clinic. I was concerned about the closure of the south China Seafood Market and asked him a few questions. He said he was back from south China (Seafood Market) , I immediately evacuated our clinic patients, informed the medical staff to protect, and reported to the hospital leadership and medical section, and other patients removed, put him in isolation.

I've been treating infectious diseases for 30 years. In the hospital, the infection department is not the most valued, the medical staff treatment is not high. I've had a lot of people change careers for liver disease or other treatments, but I've been in the infection department, and I have a professional sensitivity.

Around 4:10, the hospital leadership organized an expert consultation, highly suspected of this disease (COVID-19 pneumonia) , we did a percutaneous lung puncture under the CT machine, ruled out tuberculosis and fungi, and did blood tests, laboratory overtime examination, until 11:30 at night. For sampling, we also gave him bronchoalveolar lavage, which is a high-risk test, which we don't normally do, and this time we did it at our own risk.

Finally, we ruled out other diseases and thought it was this disease. So we reported to the Municipal Health Committee and the Municipal Committee. The municipal committee reported to the Provincial Committee. On January 9, the provincial committee sent experts over and also thought it was this disease. It was the first case of COVID-19 pneumonia in Jingzhou, and we were quick enough to nip it in the bud at first. Later, the city said, fortunately that day is my clinic, to change someone who is not engaged in infectious diseases, may cause this patient to go around, the situation is different.

At that time, COVID-19 pneumonia had appeared in Wuhan, and Jingzhou had taken some measures, but, like SARS, it did not attract much attention at first. We Hubei in this area of public information about the epidemic, at that time, we all felt that no human-to-human transmission, preventable, controllable, treatable, some misleading in it, we are not too anxious.

But his family's pretty scared. When he first came to our hospital, he had two family members with him. As soon as I said it was this disease, his family members disappeared, and I couldn't find any more family members.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Jingzhou Chest Hospital infection department morning shift, the second right is Liu Changhua

For the first week, he was getting sicker. There's no cure for viral pneumonia, it's a process, and he's on his own at the top. At one point, he developed severe respiratory failure, only 30 PSI without oxygen. Usually we normal people are 80, less than 60 means respiratory failure, and he's less than 40, which means death.

We'll give him mask oxygen, regulate his oxygen flow, and give him IVIG, which builds up his immune system, which is expensive, 600 bucks a pop for 15 grams, six a day. He has no idea what we're dealing with here. He didn't check in, he didn't pay, and we didn't think about the cost, except for the immunoglobulins, the antiviral, the anti-fungal, the hormones, everything. A special class was set up, with three nurses working eight-hour shifts to give him intensive care. He's in the isolation ward. The nurses take care of all the food and the pooping. The final cost of treatment could be over $200,000.

By January 15, he was in remission and stable. He's lucky he didn't have any underlying diseases. There are so many deaths now, most of them with underlying diseases.

That same day, our hospital received a second case, and since then, more and more people. We have 4 doctors, 11 nurses, 15 people working round the clock in the infection department and me, and people from other departments are coming to help. Hospital officials gave us an order: As long as it was suspected that the COVID-19, patients do not register, do not pay fees, direct hospitalization, no conditions.

In the beginning, we were the only designated hospital in Jingzhou, because our chest hospital had expertise in treating lung disease and respiratory disease, and other hospitals would come to us whenever they suspected, and we had several specialists look at it together, often at 10 pm or 11 pm, if the patient is consistently suspected, immediately report to the city CDC, send samples to the CDC for confirmation, nucleic acid testing needs at least 8 hours. I learned in profile that the cost of diagnosing a patient is also high, and the cost of testing is probably in the thousands. After diagnosis, we have to change the word "suspected" to "confirmed" within two hours and report it to the National Disease Control and Prevention Network, taking into account the current number of confirmed cases. We had to admit them right away, up to six or seven in one night, and we had a maximum of 65 patients in isolation beds in our hospital, and then we couldn't take them anymore, and other hospitals in Jingzhou started taking patients.

By then, Wang Ping's condition was stable, so we moved him to another unit for basic treatment. Two more nucleic acid tests later, both negative, plus most of his symptoms are gone, in line with national discharge standards, 26, we informed him to leave the hospital.

On the morning of the 27th, as he left, Wang Ping said to his bed doctor, I don't recognize you in your Hazmat suit, but when you talk, your voice tells me it's you. The three nurses who nursed him, he looked at them and said, I know you, I know you, thank you very much.

There's a confirmed patient in the hospital, he's been there for a while, he's not doing well, he's frustrated, but now that Wang Ping is out of the hospital, our first confirmed patient in Jingzhou is out of the hospital, that gives him a lot of confidence, and he's really cooperating with us, in seven to 10 days, he'll be our second confirmed discharge.
